'''Forensic genealogy''' is [[genealogy|genealogical]] research, analysis, and reporting in cases with legal implications, often involving living individuals.<ref name="CAFGwebsite">{{cite web |title=About |url=https://www.forensicgenealogists.org/about/ |website=Council for the Advancement of Forensic Genealogy |accessdate=25 July 2018}}</ref><ref name="ProGen2018">"{{cite book |last=Ramage |first=Michael S. |editor-last=Shown Mills |editor-first=Elizabeth |title=Professional Genealogy, Preparation, Practice & Standards |publisher=Genealogical Publishing Co. |date=2018 |page=337 |chapter=Chapter 15: Forensic Specialization |isbn=9780806320724}}</ref>{{rp|337}} Forensic genealogists may be called upon to appear in court to provide expert testimony, and typically furnish affidavits and research reports to their clients that adhere to the [[Genealogical Proof Standard]]<ref name="BCGstandards">{{cite book |last1=Board for Certification of Genealogists |title=Genealogy Standards |date=2014 |publisher=Ancestry.com, an imprint of Turner Publishing Co. |location=Nashville, Tennessee |isbn=978-1-630-26018-7 |pages=1–3 |edition=50th Anniversary}}</ref> established by the [[Board for Certification of Genealogists]].<ref name="OnBoardv22Sep">{{cite journal |last1=Ramage |first1=Michael S. |title=Standard and Forensic Genealogy |journal=OnBoard |date=2016 |volume=22 |issue=September |page=1 |url=https://bcgcertification.org/coming-from-onboard-september-2016 |accessdate=25 July 2018}}</ref>{{rp|1}}

==Definition==

Forensic genealogy is defined in a legal context, specifically when conducting research in the following manner:
*Estate or [[probate research]] to identify unknown and [[missing heir]]s, and potentially provide expert testimony in a courtroom;
**Unknown heir cases typically involve an individual's estate who died [[intestate]], but may also be the result of a [[remainderman]] predeceasing the [[testator]] or [[testatrix]] of a will.<ref name="PaBarAssoc76.125">{{cite journal |last1=Ramage |first1=Michael S. |title=Missing and Unknown Heir Law Practice and Procedure |journal=Pennsylvania Bar Association Quarterly |date=2005 |volume=76 |issue=July |page=125}}</ref>
**Missing heir cases involve locating [[beneficiaries]] of a will.<ref name="PaBarAssoc76.125" />
*Military repatriation: Assisting branches of the United States military in reuniting the remains of service members with their families using DNA analysis (a.k.a. [[DNA profiling]]);
*[[Kinship]] determination: Identifying family members in regard to cases of adoption, foster care, and guardianship;
*Land and real estate issues involving title, [[adverse possession]], rights of way, [[lis pendens]], or [[muniment of title]], and oil, gas, and [[mineral rights]] and royalties. Oil, gas, and mineral rights cases may be dealt with the same as unknown and missing heir cases, or [[quiet title]] actions, depending on the state with jurisdiction and the situation of the case;<ref name="RealPropJournal10">{{cite journal |last1=American Bar Association |first1=Committee on Administration and Distribution of Decedent’s Estates |title=Clearing Title of Heirs to Intestate Real Property |journal=Real Property, Probate and Trust Journal |date=1975 |volume=10 |issue=Fall |page=454 |jstor=20781390}}</ref>{{rp|454}}
**Established law in Texas gives landowners the rights to oil and gas beneath their property.<ref>{{cite web |title=Oil & Gas Exploration and Surface Ownership |url=http://www.rrc.state.tx.us/media/7124/surfaceownerinfo.pdf |website=Railroad Commission of Texas}}</ref>
*Research to help clients establish U.S. citizenship or support [[dual citizenship]] in a foreign country;
*Assisting coroner’s offices in identifying relatives of unclaimed remains;
*[[Provenance]], [[class action]] claimants, [[intellectual property rights]], etc.

A alternative definition of the field has been explained by author and scientist [[Colleen M. Fitzpatrick]], PhD, in her 2005 book ''Forensic Genealogy'',<ref name="Fitzpatrick">{{Cite book |last = Fitzpatrick |first = Colleen |title = Forensic Genealogy |publisher = Rice Book Press |date = 2005 |url = https://books.google.com/books/about/Forensic_Genealogy.html?id=AKZpAAAAMAAJ |isbn =978-0976716006 }}</ref> in which a [[forensic science]] approach is used in genealogical research. The author describes various research methods, approaches, and genealogical knowledge she has determined to be forensic in nature:
*Examining photographs for clues to pinpoint a place or time of an event. For example, a house in the background of a photo may reveal an address number, or the type of clothing worn by people can suggest when a picture was taken. Colleen Fitzpatrick has stated “The most important lesson a digital detective can ever learn is to notice what a photograph is really saying.”;<ref name="Fitzpatrick" />{{rp|4}}
*Estimating birth dates by scrutinizing marriage age laws of a jurisdiction;
*Researching “the historical context of your family”<ref name="Fitzpatrick" />{{rp|3}} to provide more insight into their lives;
*Understanding that immigrant name changes did not occur at [[Ellis Island]], but either at the immigrant’s [[embarkation]] point or years after entry to the United States;
*Analyzing [[DNA]] test results to study both matches and non-matches, as well as estimating one’s [[most recent common ancestor]] (MRCA), and discovering [[non-paternity event]]s;
*Using a Y-chromosome [[cladogram]] “to identify the main branches of a family”; etc.<ref name="Fitzpatrick">{{Cite book |last = Fitzpatrick |first = Colleen |title = Forensic Genealogy |publisher = Rice Book Press |date = 2005 |url = https://books.google.com/books/about/Forensic_Genealogy.html?id=AKZpAAAAMAAJ |isbn =978-0976716006 }}</ref>{{rp|3}}

