{{Distinguish|People's Court (Germany)}}
{{About|the People's Courts of Bavaria (1918–24)|other similarly named entities|People's Court (disambiguation)}}
[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 102-00344A, München, nach Hitler-Ludendorff Prozess.jpg|thumb|300px|Defendants in the [[Beer Hall Putsch]] trial at the People's Court in Munich]]

The '''People's Courts of [[Bavaria]]''' (''{{lang|de|Volksgerichte}}'') were ''{{lang|de|[[Sondergericht|Sondergerichte]]}}'' (special courts) established by [[Kurt Eisner]] during the [[German Revolution]] in November 1918 and part of the [[:de:Ordnungszelle|Ordnungszelle]] that lasted until May 1924 after handing out more than 31,000 sentences. It was composed of two judges and three [[lay judge]]s.{{sfn|Bauer|2009}}{{sfn|Landauer|1944|p=221}} One of its most notable trials was that of the [[Beer Hall Putsch]] conspirators, including [[Adolf Hitler]], [[Erich Ludendorff]], [[Wilhelm Frick]], [[Friedrich Weber (veterinarian)|Friedrich Weber]], and [[Ernst Röhm]], which lasted from 26 February 1924 until 1 April 1924.{{sfn|Hitler|1924}}{{sfn|Fulda|2009|pp=68–69}}

Initially established in each court district by the Order of 16 November 1918 (''{{lang|de|Verordnung vom 16 November 1918}}'') by the government of Kurt Eisner, it was furthered by the government of [[Johannes Hoffmann (SPD)|Johannes Hoffmann]] in the Law on the Establishment of People's Courts in Civil Disturbances of 12 July 1919 (''{{lang|de|Gesetz über die Einsetzung von Volksgerichten bei inneren Unruhen vom 12 Juli 1919}}'').{{sfn|Bauer|2009}} An agreement between the federal government and the government of Bavaria had fixed the deadline for the abolition of the courts on 1 April 1924.{{sfn|Landauer|1944|p=222}} In this form they remained until May 1924 after handing out more than 31,000 sentences.{{sfn|Bauer|2009}} Initially intended as a short-term solution for events surrounding the German Revolution, they became seen as part of the [[:de:Ordnungszelle|Ordnungszelle]].{{sfn|Bauer|2009}}

