'''Theriophily''' (or '''animalitarianism''') is "the inversion of human and animal traits and the argument that animals are in some way superior to men".{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}} The term theriophily was coined by [[George Boas]], while the term animalitarianism was coined by [[Arthur O. Lovejoy]] in the work ''A Documentary History of Primitivism and Related Ideas'',<ref>{{cite journal|last=Gill|first=James E.|title=Theriophily in antiquity: a supplementary account|journal=Journal of the History of Ideas|year=1969|volume=30|issue=3|url=https://www.jstor.org/pss/2708565|accessdate=6 December 2011|page=401|doi=10.2307/2708565}}</ref> in which he explained his "belief that animals are happier, more admirable, more 'normal', or 'natural', than human beings"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/animalitarianism | title=animalitarianism | publisher=Merriam-Webster, Incorporated | accessdate=December 6, 2011}}</ref> In his work ''Love for Animals'', [[Dix Harwood]] wrote "This much is certain. Between 1700 and 1800, the point of view on man's relations to other living creatures changed".<ref>{{cite book|last=Fujitani|first=James|title=Simple hearts: Animals and the religious crisis of the sixteenth century|year=2007|publisher=Proquest|isbn=978-0-549-15267-5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jIgkJk-V58wC&dq=Theriophily&source=gbs_navlinks_s|accessdate=6 December 2011|page=1}}</ref>
[[Leonardo Da Vinci]] touches upon the subject in ''[[Studies on the Life and Habits of Animals]]'', [[Jonathan Swift]] wrote about human inferiority in ''[[Gulliver's Travels]]'' and [[Mark Twain]] detailed various ways that humans could be shown to be inferior to other animals in [[Letters from the Earth]].

